// New 2026-07-18: the watch's own body/case (crown, both chronograph pushers, bracelet links)
// shown behind the dial instead of plain black - user wanted the "big triangular areas" around the
// round dial (and the top/bottom letterbox) to show real watch material instead of empty black.
// Built by pattern-matching (OpenCV, Canny-edge multi-scale+rotation template match) the *existing*
// face_citizen_410_dial_img against the original full-body studio photo
// (CitizenE-DriveRedArrowsRAFA_900x.webp - the same one this face's dial content originally traces
// back to, just never cropped/used for anything beyond the dial itself until now) - this finds the
// scale/rotation/position that makes the existing dial align with its own appearance inside the
// full photo, rather than re-deriving the crop by eye (the earlier "crown/pusher bias" problem
// logged elsewhere in this file is exactly the kind of error that method avoids). Best match:
// scale 0.804, rotation 0.0 deg, matched blend overlay showed clean alignment of the bezel scale
// numbers/ticks with only minor softness, no visible doubling.
//
// Cropped to the full 410x494 screen at that matched transform, hard-clipped (crown falls entirely
// outside the 410px width at this scale and is simply not visible - user was fine with that). Real
// content that lands in the four corners around where the round dial sits: bracelet lugs. Original
// photo's plain white studio background flood-filled to black from the image borders (geometric
// flood fill anchored at all four edges, not a blanket brightness threshold, so it doesn't touch
// bright/reflective metal *on* the watch - only the region actually connected to the border).
//
// Re-shifted 3px left 2026-07-20: dial/hands/text stay exactly where they are (fixed anchor, see
// citizen_410.c's DIAL_SHIFT_X) - only this case picture moves, to correct for the dial reading
// slightly right-of-center against it. Re-derived the exact original webp crop rectangle by
// matching a still-existing verification image (match_compare.png, right panel) from the original
// 07-18 session back against the same source photo (0.976 confidence, scale 0.8039 vs the
// documented 0.804, rotation effectively 0 - consistent with the original numbers, confirming the
// recovered rectangle is correct) rather than trusting written notes alone, then shifted that
// rectangle's x-origin by 3px/0.8039 =~3.73 webp px and re-cropped/re-flood-filled fresh from the
// original photo - the newly-exposed ~3.7px strip on the right is genuine photo content, not
// synthesized.
//
// Flood-fill bug fixed same day: the first attempt seeded flood-fill from every border pixel
// without checking color first - the bracelet touches the top/bottom crop edges with its own dark
// metal tones, so those became bad seed origins and flood-filled outward from grey, eating the
// connected crown/pusher/bracelet detail (confirmed visually - crown and both pushers had nearly
// vanished into black). Fixed by only seeding from border pixels that are genuinely near-white
// (min channel > 220) before flood-filling - crown/pusher detail confirmed back, matching or
// slightly exceeding the original asset's level of detail.
//
// Opaque RGB565 (no alpha - drawn as the base layer, face_citizen_410_dial_img draws on top of it
// with its own now-transparent corners, see that file's header comment).

#include "../citizen_410.h"

